### If a component isn't installed yet, add it — don't rebuild it

```bash
npx shadcn@latest add @byronwade/<name>
# e.g. npx shadcn@latest add @byronwade/sheet @byronwade/command
```

Transitive dependencies resolve automatically (`add @byronwade/activity-ring` pulls `status-dot` + `utils`).
Only build a brand-new component when nothing in the list above fits — and when you do, follow
sections 2–4 so it looks like it belongs.

## 2. Style with tokens only — never hardcode color

**Never** write hex (`#16a34a`), `rgb()`, `hsl()`, named CSS colors, or arbitrary color values
like `text-[#333]`. Always use the semantic token utilities. They adapt to light/dark and to
re-skinning automatically:

| Need             | Use                                                                                                                                                                             | Never                         |
| ---------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | ----------------------------- |
| Page / surface   | `bg-background`, `bg-card`, `bg-popover`                                                                                                                                        | `bg-white`, `bg-[#fff]`       |
| Text             | `text-foreground`, `text-muted-foreground`                                                                                                                                      | `text-black`, `text-gray-500` |
| Primary action   | `bg-primary text-primary-foreground`                                                                                                                                            | `bg-blue-600`                 |
| Brand / accent   | `bg-brand`, `text-brand`, `bg-brand-muted`                                                                                                                                      | `bg-green-500`                |
| Success          | `bg-success`, `text-success`                                                                                                                                                    | `text-green-600`              |
| Warning          | `bg-warning`, `text-warning`                                                                                                                                                    | `text-amber-500`              |
| Error / danger   | `bg-destructive`, `text-destructive`                                                                                                                                            | `text-red-500`                |
| Borders / inputs | `border-border`, `bg-input`                                                                                                                                                     | `border-gray-200`             |
| Focus ring       | `ring-ring` (already on primitives)                                                                                                                                             | custom outline                |
| Muted fill       | `bg-muted`, `bg-secondary`, `bg-accent`                                                                                                                                         | `bg-gray-100`                 |
| Sidebar          | `bg-sidebar`, `text-sidebar-foreground`, …                                                                                                                                      | —                             |
| Dock             | `bg-dock`, `text-dock-foreground`, `bg-dock-muted`, `bg-dock-active`, `text-dock-active-foreground`, `bg-dock-tool` (lighter tool-zone shelf for two-tone combined nav+toolbar) | `bg-zinc-900`                 |
| Charts           | `--chart-1` … `--chart-5` (via `chart`)                                                                                                                                         | fixed palettes                |
| Agent activity   | `bg-activity-thinking`, `bg-activity-search`, `bg-activity-read`, `bg-activity-edit` (+ `text-activity-*`)                                                                      | bespoke pastels               |

Tone the same token with opacity instead of new colors: `bg-brand/10`, `text-destructive`,
`bg-success/10`. This is the house pattern for soft chips and rings (see `status-pill`).

### Radius and spacing

Use the radius scale, never raw pixels: `rounded-sm`, `rounded-md`, `rounded-lg`, `rounded-xl`,
`rounded-2xl` … `rounded-4xl` (all derived from `--radius`). Pills use `rounded-full`.

### Typography — editorial restraint

The system reads as a calm, warm, editorial canvas. Express hierarchy through **size + tight
tracking + the typeface**, not through heavy weight or color. Base styles already apply the tracking
(`h1–h4` carry `-0.02em`); your job is to not fight them.

- **Display / page headings stay light.** Set large headings at `font-normal` (or at most
  `font-medium`) — **never `font-bold`** for hero/section titles. Bold is reserved for genuinely
  emphatic inline runs, not headlines. A regular-weight headline with tight tracking is the house look.
- **Mono for metadata.** Use `font-mono` for the things that are _data_: numeric stats and metrics,
  prices, timestamps, durations, counts, IDs, hashes, slugs, filenames, keyboard hints (`kbd`), model
  names, tool names, JSON/code-like parameters, agent logs, and small technical labels. This gives the
  UI its crisp, engineered texture without making the interface feel like a code editor. Body copy,
  navigation labels, button labels, form labels, and headings stay `font-sans`.
- **Serif for editorial moments only.** `font-serif` (backed by the `--font-serif` token) is for
  long-form prose, pull quotes, and blockquotes — not UI chrome. Reach for it via `reading-prose` on
  essay and article surfaces.

### Icons — Phosphor, duotone by default

Icons are part of the system's voice, not a free-for-all. Every icon resolves to **one barrel** and
renders in **duotone** unless a state needs otherwise.

- **Always import from `@/lib/icons`.** Never import `lucide-react`, `@phosphor-icons/react`,
  `react-icons`, or any other icon package directly, and never hand-roll an icon `<svg>`. The barrel
  re-exports [Phosphor](https://phosphoricons.com) under its exact catalog names — `CaretDown`,
  `MagnifyingGlass`, `Gear`, `Trash`, `DotsThree`, `House`, `Envelope`, `Warning`, `Check`, `X`,
  `Heart`, `Sparkle`, and so on. (Add it with `npx shadcn@latest add @byronwade/icons`; it comes in
  automatically with any component that uses icons.)
- **Duotone is the default — don't restate it.** The barrel owns the weight the way `--brand` owns the
  accent, so write `<Heart className="size-5 text-brand" />`, not `weight="duotone"`. Override only
  when a state calls for it: `weight="bold" | "fill" | "regular" | "thin" | "light"`.
- **Token color, scale size.** Color comes from tokens through `currentColor` (`text-brand`,
  `text-muted-foreground`, `text-destructive`), never a raw value or the `color` prop. Size comes from
  the scale (`size-4`, `size-5`), not the `size` prop.
- **Type icon-shaped props** with `Icon` / `IconProps` from `@/lib/icons` (e.g.
  `icon?: Icon`, `Record<Tone, Icon>`).

```tsx
import { Heart, MagnifyingGlass, type Icon } from "@/lib/icons"

// duotone by default; tint via currentColor, size via the scale
<Heart className="size-5 text-brand" />
<MagnifyingGlass weight="bold" className="size-4 text-muted-foreground" />
```

### Readability — two lanes (evidence-backed)

Web reading on emissive screens follows different rules than print or e-ink. byronwade/ui encodes
peer-reviewed parameters in foundation utilities — not as optional polish, but as the house standard
for anything meant to be _read_.

- **UI lane** — `font-sans`, `text-sm`/`text-base`, tight tracking (`-0.006em` on body). Dashboards,
  forms, nav, tables. Never below 16px for copy users must read in flow.
- **Docs lane** — `reading-ui`: 65ch measure, 16px sans, 1.6 line height, 1.5em paragraph gap,
  neutral letter-spacing. Guides, release notes, in-app help.
- **Essay lane** — `reading-prose`: 65ch measure, 18px serif, 1.7 line height, same paragraph gap.
  Articles, manifestos, marketing essays.
- **Measure cap** — `reading-measure` alone when you need the width without typography. Never exceed
  **80ch** (WCAG 1.4.8). Target **65ch** (Dyson & Haselgrove, 55 CPL optimal zone).
- **Left-align body** — no justified paragraphs. Token contrast only (`foreground` on `background`).
- **No hacks** — no Bionic Reading, no e-ink sepia simulation, no bold-first-word gimmicks (no
  evidence base).

**Agent routing (copy meant to be read):**

| You are building…                   | Use                                                                 |
| ----------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| Dashboard, form, table, nav         | UI lane — `font-sans`, `text-sm`/`text-base`                        |
| Guide, help, release notes          | `reading-ui` + `text-foreground`                                    |
| Essay, article, long marketing copy | `reading-prose` + `text-foreground`                                 |
| Need width cap only                 | `reading-measure`                                                   |
| Article page layout                 | `marketing-layout variant="article"` (sections are `reading-prose`) |
| Docs marketing layout               | `marketing-layout variant="docs-marketing"` (main is `reading-ui`)  |

Never stack negative body tracking on reading utilities — foundation resets `letter-spacing: 0` there.

- **`reading-lead`** — optional opener paragraph inside a reading lane (1.125rem sans / 1.25rem prose).
- **`reading-muted`** — secondary copy inside a reading lane; higher contrast than `text-muted-foreground`.
- **`reading-demo-break`** — full-width band above demos/previews; separates 65ch prose from wide specimens.

### Two surfaces, one foundation

Application UI and marketing/editorial share tokens and `--brand` — they diverge in typography lane and layout density. Do **not** split the registry into two packages; route by surface instead.

| Surface                   | Typography                                               | Layout                                      | Example components                                |
| ------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------- |
| **Application UI**        | UI lane — `font-sans`, `text-sm`/`text-base`             | Shells, tables, forms, dense dashboards     | `app-shell`, `sidebar`, `table`, `morph-dock`     |
| **Marketing & editorial** | Essay lane — `reading-prose` for copy; heroes full-bleed | `marketing-layout`, media shelves, commerce | `hero-section`, `marketing-layout`, `video-shelf` |

Media, Video, and Commerce categories are marketing surface. `hero-section`, `marketing-layout`, and `description-box` are marketing even when filed under Composites/Patterns.

**Density routing:**

| Task density              | Use when                                                                      | Treatment                                                                                        |
| ------------------------- | ----------------------------------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------ |
| **Dense operational**     | Tables, admin indexes, dashboards, command centers, kanban, gantt, file trees | Compact spacing, stable row heights, clear separators, mono metadata, no decorative color fields |
| **Comfortable product**   | Setup flows, settings, empty states, detail pages, cards                      | Token spacing with visible grouping, `text-sm`/`text-base`, calm actions                         |
| **Editorial / marketing** | Guides, articles, launch pages, commerce/media surfaces                       | Reading lanes, full-bleed media where useful, larger rhythm without card nesting                 |

### House utilities (already defined by `foundation`)

`bg-grid`, `bg-grid-lines`, `glow-brand`, `text-gradient`, `text-gradient-brand`, `mask-fade-x`,
`mask-fade-l`, `mask-fade-r`, `full-bleed`, `edge`, `depth-none`, `depth-soft`, `depth-raised`, `depth-100`, `depth-200`, `depth-300`,
`depth-400`, `depth-500`, `depth-600`, `depth-inset-100`, `depth-inset-200`, `scrollbar-thin`, `reading-measure`, `reading-ui`, `reading-prose`,
`reading-lead`, `reading-muted`, `reading-demo-break`. Prefer these over
re-implementing gradients, grids, or shadows by hand.

A few utilities hold a deliberate **fixed-color exception** that tokens can't express — the raw value
lives here in `foundation`, audited in one place, never inline in a component: `scrim-top` (top-down
dark scrim for image legibility), `scrim-bottom` (bottom-up foreground scrim for overlay text),
`scrim-top-background` / `scrim-bottom-background` (background-toned scrims for player chrome),
`color-picker-hue` (the hue rainbow), `color-picker-alpha-fade`
(the alpha transparency fade). Use the utility; don't re-roll the gradient in markup.

### Depth follows Shopify Polaris — shadowless by default

Surfaces are **shadowless by default**. Resting components use spacing, background tokens, and the
inset `edge` hairline instead of default elevation. The `edge` utility is the flat baseline
(`box-shadow: inset 0 0 0 1px var(--edge)`): faint dark in light mode, faint light in dark mode.

When depth is needed, use the Shopify Polaris-compatible depth utilities only. The foundation carries
the Polaris primitive scale (`--shadow-0`, `--shadow-100` ... `--shadow-600`,
`--shadow-bevel-100`, `--shadow-inset-100`, `--shadow-inset-200`). `depth-soft` maps to the Polaris
resting surface pairing (`--shadow-100` + bevel), and `depth-raised` maps to the Polaris elevated
popover/tooltip pairing (`--shadow-300` + bevel). Deeper surfaces use the explicit scale:
`depth-400` for toasts and `depth-600` for modal/search-style overlays. In dark mode, keep the same
Polaris elevation scale but use the dark-calibrated bevel token so depth reads darker, not like a
white glow. Do not use Tailwind's generic `shadow-*` utilities or custom `box-shadow` values in
component code.

- **Every surface** — floating overlays (dialog, popover, dropdown-menu, hover-card, command,
  select, sheet, navigation-menu, morph-dock panels) AND resting surfaces (card, stat-card, section,
  data-table wrappers, command panels, file-tree panels, editor frames) AND flat containers (inline
  alert, list container) — uses the **`edge`** utility and carries **no** `border`. Overlays are crisp
  and flat; the hairline separates them. (Filled decorative shapes like `gradient-avatar` are the
  exception — no hairline; for stacks use `ring-background`.)
- **Borders are for separators only** — a divider between regions (`border-t`, `border-b`,
  table-row dividers), an input/affordance edge (`border-input`), or a genuinely subtle line that
  breaks an element from a same-colored background. Never reach for a `border` to outline a surface;
  let the `--edge` hairline do it. No raw colors here either — the hairline is token-driven, so a
  consumer overriding nothing still gets correct light/dark depth.
- **Input affordances stay inputs** — `border-input` belongs on input-like controls and handles. If
  that control sits inside a framed panel, put `edge` on the panel wrapper; don't double-outline the
  control itself.

## 3. Re-skinning is one variable — leave the rest alone

The entire accent (rings, primary chart line, active states, success) follows `--brand`.
To re-theme, override **only** `--brand` in your `globals.css`:

```css
:root {
  --brand: oklch(0.55 0.2 25);
} /* light */
.dark {
  --brand: oklch(0.65 0.2 25);
} /* dark  */
```

Do **not** edit other foundation tokens, hardcode the green, or fork `globals.css` token values
to achieve a color. If the design needs a different accent, change `--brand`.

**Two deliberate exceptions** do **not** follow `--brand` — they are fixed, semantic palettes:
the **chart** ramp (`--chart-2…5`) and the **agent-activity** pastels (`--activity-thinking`,
`--activity-search`, `--activity-read`, `--activity-edit`). The activity set encodes what an AI agent
is _doing_ (thinking / searching / reading / editing) for agent composites like `event-timeline`,
`verification-progress`, `activity-ring`, and `conversation-list`. Use them via `bg-activity-*` /
`text-activity-*`; tone with opacity for soft chips (`bg-activity-read/15`). Don't repurpose them as
a general accent — they carry meaning.

### Semantic color expansion policy

The default answer to a color request is: use `--brand`, an existing status token, an existing chart
token, or an existing activity token. Add a new fixed color family only when all of these are true:

1. It encodes domain meaning, state, or data class that cannot be represented by the existing tokens.
2. The token is named by meaning, not hue (`activity-read`, not `blue-pastel`).
3. The allowed components and use cases are documented in `AGENTS.md` and this shipped rule.
4. The values live in the `foundation` item, with utilities/examples/tests when component-facing.
5. The palette is never introduced for visual variety, brand taste, or one-off decoration.

## 4. Component conventions (match these when extending or composing)

- **Primitives are built on Base UI** (`@base-ui/react`) with **CVA** variants and
  **`data-slot`** attributes. New variants belong in the component's `cva(...)`, not as one-off
  `className` overrides at call sites.
- **Always merge classes with `cn()`** from `@/lib/utils` and accept a `className` prop so callers
  can extend without breaking base styles.
- **Accessibility is non-optional**: keep labels, `aria-*`, keyboard behavior, and the built-in
  `focus-visible:ring-ring`. Don't strip focus rings or outlines.
- **Dark mode is automatic** through tokens — if you only use token utilities, dark mode just works.
  Never branch on a hardcoded color for dark mode.
- Compose composites from primitives (e.g. `status-pill` = `status-dot` + tokens); follow that
  pattern instead of new bespoke elements.

### Object-bound AI and agent surfaces

AI UI must be attached to the object it is acting on: a conversation, task, source, file, issue,
verification step, tool call, model event, or proposed change. Avoid free-floating "AI magic" surfaces
that do not expose what changed, where it came from, and what the user can review.

- Show state explicitly: pending, running, succeeded, failed, needs approval, or reverted.
- Expose provenance on conversational/agent surfaces. `Message` uses `data-provenance` for `user`,
  `assistant`, `system`, `tool`, `app`, `source`, or `action`; `MessageProvenance` provides a compact
  mono label when authorship, grounding, embedded app output, or proposed action origin matters.
- `PromptInput` defaults to `data-provenance="user"` and can be overridden for embedded app/action
  composers. Follow OpenAI/Twenty-style physical clarity: compact/default/comfortable density must
  change textarea min-height, padding, footer/header rhythm, and control sizing; inset frames and
  shadow states must change containment and elevation, not just background color. Do not add visible
  prompt metadata chips unless the product workflow specifically needs them.
- `Tool`, `Sources`, and `Source` carry provenance attributes so consumers can inspect and style
  agent output by origin without recoloring the whole surface.
- Use `bg-activity-*` / `text-activity-*` only for the agent's activity type: thinking, searching,
  reading, or editing.
- Use `font-mono` for tool names, model names, parameters, IDs, file paths, and logs.
- Destructive or irreversible AI actions require an approval affordance (`ai-confirmation`, dialog,
  or equivalent review step).
- Compose agent surfaces from primitives and existing AI components; do not invent one-off colored
  panels.

### Comparison-informed component guidance

Use the design research as behavior guidance, not visual cloning:

- `table`, `data-table`, and index views follow Shopify/Linear density: stable row heights, scan-first
  hierarchy, mono metadata, token separators, no decorative row color.
- `tag-input`, status tags, and record metadata follow Twenty: keep the field/container neutral and
  color the data object itself. Use semantic tones (`neutral`, `brand`, `success`, `warning`,
  `destructive`) through existing badge/tag variants; add a broader fixed palette only for documented
  domain meaning.
- `command` and `command-result` follow Vercel/Linear command behavior: compact, keyboard-first,
  previewable, with `kbd` and technical labels in mono.
- `kanban` and `gantt` follow Linear/Atlassian planning clarity: status and ownership are explicit,
  density stays readable, and colors map to meaning.
- `file-tree`, editor, and deployment surfaces follow Vercel/Cursor framing: paths and versions are
  mono, panels use `edge`, and hierarchy comes from indentation and object state.
- `event-timeline`, `activity-ring`, `verification-progress`, and AI components follow Cursor/Linear:
  activity is object-bound, stateful, reviewable, and colored only by activity semantics.

## Quick self-check before you finish UI work

1. Did I solve a real user/teammate problem (not just add UI)?
2. Did I cover every state, edge case, and interaction — not only the happy path?
3. Did I use an existing `@byronwade/ui` component instead of a raw element?
4. Are all colors semantic tokens (no hex/rgb/named/arbitrary colors)?
5. Is radius from the scale, and did I use `cn()` + a `className` passthrough?
6. Did I leave foundation tokens alone and only consider `--brand` for theming?
7. Are focus states, labels, and keyboard behavior intact?
8. Is long-form copy on `reading-ui` or `reading-prose` (not full-bleed `text-sm` sans)?
9. Is reading measure ≤ 80ch (target 65ch via the reading utilities)?
10. Is `font-mono` limited to real data or technical metadata?
11. Are all icons imported from `@/lib/icons` (Phosphor, duotone default, token color, scale size) — no other icon package and no hand-rolled `<svg>`?
12. Do framed surfaces use `edge` instead of outline borders or shadows?
13. If this is AI UI, is it attached to an object/action with clear state and review?
14. If I introduced a color family, did it pass the semantic expansion policy?

If any answer is "no", fix it before moving on.
